Step 1: The first $8$ positive odd integers are $1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15.$ We need to find the modulo $16$ inverse of each of these numbers and then sum them.

The inverse of $a$ modulo $m$ is an integer $x$ such that $ax\equiv 1\pmod m.$
Step 2: 
\begin{align*}
\overline{1}^{-1}&\equiv 1\pmod{16},\\
\overline{3}^{-1}&\equiv 11\pmod{16},\\
\overline{5}^{-1}&\equiv 13\pmod{16},\\
\overline{7}^{-1}&\equiv 9\pmod{16},\\
\overline{9}^{-1}&\equiv 3\pmod{16},\\
\overline{11}^{-1}&\equiv 7\pmod{16},\\
\overline{13}^{-1}&\equiv 15\pmod{16},\\
\overline{15}^{-1}&\equiv 15\pmod{16}.
\end{align*}
Step 3:
\begin{align*}
1+11+13+9+3+7+15+15&=74\\
\Rightarrow \qquad 74 \pmod{16} &\equiv \boxed{2}
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
74 \pmod{16} &\equiv 2\pmod{16}\\
\end{align*}
